{
  "doc_id": "25397",
  "text": "We studied these issues in the three-spine stickleback Gasterosteus aculeatus, a shoaling fish species [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] that is frequently used as a model for studying collective behaviour [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Water temperatures in this species' natural habitat can show wide temporal and spatial variation, in some cases spanning a 158C range on daily and annual bases [CITATION_6] . This makes it an ideal species for studying general behavioural responses to thermal heterogeneity which remain relevant to the animal's natural ecology. Specifically, we aimed to address the following questions: (i) do individuals differ in their preferred temperature?; (ii) do individuals vary in the extent to which they will deviate from their own preferred temperature to associate with conspecifics? and (iii) does the willingness to deviate from a preferred thermal regime depend on interactions among sociability, temperature preference and metabolic traits? Our results provide insight into the relative costs and benefits of sociability and the extent to which environmental temperature can shape interactions between individual animals and their social environment.",
